Paul Krugman wrote about this topic today. [See https://www.nytimes.com/2022/07/15/opinion/euro-dollar-fed-ecb.html]. There are two principal reasons for the weak euro/dollar exchange rate. Europe, and especially Germany, bet heavily on low-cost Russian energy. They also bet on exports to China. Both choices are problematic now, but especially their willful blindness to the Russia threat.

Initial highly subjective forecast, loosely guided by visual extrapolation from the past 3-6 month trend. Surprising new developments in the relative outlook for Eurozone OR the US remain possible, so making sure to add some probability to even the more extreme outcomes.

The pessimistic scenarios the eurozone faces economically, and with a summer that looks like it will include significant climate related damage, especially in the weaker economies in southern and eastern Europe, there is little optimism for a strong euro while demand for the dollar should remain strong.

Starting with a fairly wide spread centred around a further 5 to 10% loss that is in line with recent months. I dont expect the current trend to change anytime soon, and October is not too far away. The current question is then about how much the euro can fall against the dollar in an unprecedented context (with respect to the life of the euro). With inflation, particularly due to energy prices that are tied to the dollar (with even greater dependency on the US for oil and LNG now), the generally pessimistic scenarios the eurozone faces economically, and with a summer that looks like it will include significant climate related damage, especially in the weaker economies in southern Europe, there will be little appetite for euros while demand for the dollar should remain strong.
